{"award_age":83.0,"bio_image":"full\/203715a3d006e70c74ac25bd2d3c0b1c533c7aa3.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1905-04-18T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1998-02-27T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/f\/fa\/George_H._Hitchings_1988.jpg\/220px-George_H._Hitchings_1988.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_H._Hitchings","mini_bio":"<p><b>George Herbert Hitchings<\/b> (April 18, 1905 \u2013 February 27, 1998) was an <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States\" title=\"United States\">American<\/a> doctor who shared the 1988 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine<\/a> with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Sir_James_Black\" title=\"Sir James Black\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Sir James Black<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Gertrude_Elion\" title=\"Gertrude Elion\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Gertrude Elion<\/a> \"for their discoveries of important principles for drug treatment,\" Hitchings specifically for his work on <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Chemotherapy\" title=\"Chemotherapy\">chemotherapy<\/a>.<\/p><p>Hitchings was born in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hoquiam,_Washington\" title=\"Hoquiam, Washington\">Hoquiam, Washington<\/a>, in 1905, and grew up there, in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Berkeley,_California\" title=\"Berkeley, California\">Berkeley, California<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/San_Diego\" title=\"San Diego\">San Diego<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Bellingham,_Washington\" title=\"Bellingham, Washington\">Bellingham, Washington<\/a>, and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Seattle\" title=\"Seattle\">Seattle<\/a>. He graduated from Seattle's <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Seattle_Public_Schools\" title=\"Seattle Public Schools\">Franklin High School<\/a>, where he was <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Salutatorian\" title=\"Salutatorian\">salutatorian<\/a>, in 1923, and from there went to the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Washington\" title=\"University of Washington\">University of Washington<\/a>, from which he graduated with a degree in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Chemistry\" title=\"Chemistry\">chemistry<\/a> <i>cum laude<\/i> in 1927, after having been elected to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Phi_Beta_Kappa\" title=\"Phi Beta Kappa\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Phi Beta Kappa<\/a> as a junior the year before. That summer, he worked at the university's <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Puget_Sound\" title=\"Puget Sound\">Puget Sound<\/a> Biological Station at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Friday_Harbor,_Washington\" title=\"Friday Harbor, Washington\">Friday Harbor<\/a> on <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/San_Juan_Island\" title=\"San Juan Island\">San Juan Island<\/a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"http:\/\/depts.washington.edu\/fhl\/\">[1]<\/a>, and received a master's degree the next year for his thesis based on that work.<\/p><p>From the University of Washington, Hitchings went to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Harvard_University\" title=\"Harvard University\">Harvard University<\/a> as a teaching fellow, ending up at Harvard Medical School. Before getting his <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Doctor_of_Philosophy\" title=\"Doctor of Philosophy\">Ph.D.<\/a> in 1933, he joined <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Alpha_Chi_Sigma\" title=\"Alpha Chi Sigma\">Alpha Chi Sigma<\/a> in 1929. During the next ten years, he would work at Harvard and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Case_Western_Reserve_University\" title=\"Case Western Reserve University\">Case Western Reserve University<\/a>. In 1942, he went to work for <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/GlaxoSmithKline\" title=\"GlaxoSmithKline\">Wellcome Research Laboratories<\/a>, where he began working with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Gertrude_Elion\" title=\"Gertrude Elion\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Gertrude Elion<\/a> in 1944. Drugs Hitchings' team worked on included <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/2,6-diaminopurine\" title=\"2,6-diaminopurine\" class=\"mw-redirect\">2,6-diaminopurine<\/a> (a compound to treat <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Leukemia\" title=\"Leukemia\">leukemia<\/a>) and <a href=\"\/w\/index.php?title=P-chlorophenoxy-2,4-diaminopyrimidine&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"P-chlorophenoxy-2,4-diaminopyrimidine (page does not exist)\">p-chlorophenoxy-2,4-diaminopyrimidine<\/a> (a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Folic_acid\" title=\"Folic acid\">folic acid<\/a> antagonist). According to his Nobel Prize autobiography,<\/p><p>In 1967 Hitchings became Vice President in Charge of Research of Burroughs-Wellcome. He became Scientist Emeritus in 1976. He also served as an adjunct faculty member at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Duke_University_School_of_Medicine\" title=\"Duke University School of Medicine\">Duke University School of Medicine<\/a>. Hitchings died in 1998 in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Chapel_Hill,_North_Carolina\" title=\"Chapel Hill, North Carolina\">Chapel Hill, North Carolina<\/a>. Hitchings founded the Triangle Community Foundation in 1983. Hitchings is a member of the Medicinal Chemistry Hall of Fame. His wife died in 1985.<\/p>","name":"George H. Hitchings","place_of_birth":"Hoquiam, Washington","place_of_death":null,"text":"George H. Hitchings , Physiology or Medicine, 1988","year":1988.0}